Introduction

Giant buttercup is generally the most aggressive of the buttercups in New Zealand. Cattle will not eat the plant throughout most of the year which makes it much more of a problem on dairy farms. In dairy regions where giant buttercup exists, it can be a major problem. Such areas include Taranaki, Nelson Bays and near Woodville. The control of giant buttercup has never been particularly easy, many would think that use of herbicides would be the most effective way to get rid of this invasive weed, but this is not the case with the Giant Buttercup. There have been problems in some areas with biotypes of giant buttercup which have developed resistance to herbicides. An experiment was carried out to investigate the efficacy of different herbicides and management of pasture on the weed, giant buttercup (Ranunculus Acris), growth in dairy pastures. Two paddocks in each of nine farms were used for the experiment and in each paddock a randomized layout was used with eight herbicide treatments including a Nil control and plots mown, or not, before each grazing or not. There are two factors to be fitted (Herbicide and Mow) in the analysis. The measured variable for question 1 is the percent cover of buttercup in each plot (Buttercuppc). The measured variable for question 2 is the number of 10cm by 10cm squares of bare ground in each plot (BareGrnd). The plots were 10 metres by 2 metres so although there is a maximum value none of the observations approach this so we can approximate this variable as an unbounded count. There is a interaction term between Farm and Paddock. When we have the percent cover of buttercup in each plot, we fit a simple analysis of variance and a random effects model with fixed effect for both Mow and Herbicides and their interaction and a term for the Farm by Paddock interaction. When we have the number of 10cm by 10cm squares of bare ground in each plot (BareGrnd), we fit a a Generalised Linear model and a Generalised Linear mixed to the data with fixed effect for both Mow and Herbicide and their interaction and a random effect for the Farm by Paddock interaction.

There are 864 random data collected in the original dataset. Two paddocks in each of nine farms were used for the experiment and in each paddock a randomized layout was used with eight herbicide treatments including a Nil control and plots mown, or not, before each grazing or not. So, Farm, Paddock, Herbicide and Mow are the predictive variables, and Buttercuppc are the response variable.

We first remove observations that are missing salary values, and log-transformation Buttercuppc so that its distribution has more of a typical bell-shape.

By inspecting the dataset, there are certainly some missing values. Before doing the further analysis, the missing values were removed from the dataset.

Exploratory data analysis was used to explore the dataset further. Boxplots were used as a graphical display of the variables to check for any extreme values, influential outliers, distribution of the variables and an overall insight of the data.

Boxplot of farm by paddock showed that the percent cover of buttercup didnt vary much depending on the farm. There is no obvious pattern to which the buttercuppc was higher in dry or wet paddock.

2.

log-transformation Buttercuppc so that its distribution has more of a typical bell-shape.

hist(buttercup$Buttercuppc, main="Histogram of percent cover of buttercup in each plot", xlab="Percent Cover of Buttercup")

#generating interaction terms
buttercup$buttercuppc_log <- log(buttercup$Buttercuppc+0.001)
hist(buttercup$buttercuppc_log, main="Histogram of log percent cover of buttercup in each plot", xlab = "Log of Percent Cover of Buttercup")

A histogram of percent cover of buttercup in each plot was used to show the important features. Since the responsible variable showed a highly skewed distribution, a log transformation was performed. If there were any 0 values and because log(0) is undefined, so 0.001 was added to each value of the Buttercuppc. Hence, another histogram of the log transformed Buttercuppc was plotted. From now on, the value of 0.001 added onto buttercuppc then log transformed will be referred to Buttercuppc or percent cover of buttercup. The histogram of log percent cover of buttercup in each plot is generated, which shows a more bell- shaped distribution.

3.

A simple analysis of variance model was fitted to the data including the interaction between Herbicide and Mow and a term for the Farm and Paddock.

# A new variable is generated, which is the interaction between the Farm and Paddock variables.
farm_by_paddock <- interaction(buttercup$Farm, buttercup$Paddock)
fit1 <- aov(buttercuppc_log~Herbicide*Mow+farm_by_paddock, data=buttercup)
summary(fit1)

4.

Discuss the general conclusion:

The summary output of the ANOVA for the model including the interaction between Herbicide and Mow and interaction for the Farm and Paddock showed that Mow and Herbicide are both associated with percent cover of buttercup in each plot. The relationship we saw in the box plot earlier is also evident. The p-values of these variables were less than 0.05 (<2e-16 and 0.0471 for Herbicide and Mow respectively). But the p-value for Mow was very close to the significance level 0.05, which means the Mow fixed effect was not as statistically significant as the Herbicide fixed effect. Hence, Mow was not as strongly associated to percent cover of buttercup than Herbicide.

However, the p-value for Herbicide and Mow interaction (0.1605) was greater than 0.05. So, Herbicide and Mow interaction is not statistically significant. This suggested that whether a plot has been mown or not didnt make a difference for the herbicides and what herbicide was used didnt influence whether the plot was mown or not.

The p-value for Farm and Paddock interaction (<2e-16) was less than 0.05. So, the term is statistically significant. This suggested that the main effects, Farm and Paddock, would not be interpretable without considering the interaction effect between Farm and Paddock because whether the paddock was dry or wet depended on the farm. This also indicated that the relationship between Farm and percent cover of buttercup in each plot depended on whether the paddock was dry or wet.

Fit a random effects model with the Farm by Paddock variable as the random effect and fixed effects for mowing and herbicides and their interaction in the model.

library(lme4)
## Loading required package: Matrix

#is.factor(buttercup$Mow)
#levels(buttercup$Herbicide)
# Herbicide and Mow are factors and make the Nil control as the baseline 
buttercup <- within(buttercup,Herbicide <- relevel(Herbicide,ref = "Nil"))
mod2 <-lmer(buttercup$buttercuppc_log~Herbicide*Mow+(1|farm_by_paddock),data=buttercup)

  1. i

The Farm by Paddock effect in the simple ANOVA model shows that Farm by Paddock explained 69.16% percent of the total variability. This is computed by dividing the sums of squared of Farm by Paddock (2086), by the residual sums of squares (3016).

  1. ii

Using the variance for Farm by Paddock random effect, it shows that 68.52% of total variability was explained. This is computed by dividing the variance of Farm by Paddock (2.636), by the variance of residual (3.847). we notice that 69.16% and 68.52% are very close. Hence, the Farm by Paddock explains a useful amount of total variability, which is 68.52%.

2.(a)

Look at the distribution of BareGrnd by showing the histogram. Justify the distribution used for the response variable.

#histogram of response variable
hist(buttercup$BareGrnd)

The histogram of the number of 10cm x 10cm squares of bare ground shows a poisson distribution.

The distribution for the response variable, BareGrnd, is poisson distribution. Poisson regression is a generalized linear model form of regression analysis used to model count data. Count data is a type of data which consists of non-negative integers. The response variable, BareGrnd, is the number of 10cm by 10cm squares of bare ground in each plot which is count data.

2.(b)

Fit the GLM and dicuss the result

glm1<- glm(BareGrnd~Herbicide*Mow+farm_by_paddock, family="poisson",data=buttercup)
#summary(glm1) #better AIC 17515
glm1.1 <- glm(BareGrnd~Herbicide*Mow+farm_by_paddock, family="quasipoisson",data=buttercup)
summary(glm1.1)$coef[1:3,]
##                                  Estimate Std. Error   t value      Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)                     4.3345512 0.09432061 45.955506 1.189141e-224
## HerbicideAminopyralid           0.3009473 0.08330380  3.612648  3.224015e-04
## HerbicideAminopyralid+triclopyr 0.3250091 0.08288155  3.921369  9.575650e-05
#summary(glm1.1)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(glm1.1)

The summary output of the GLM including the fixed effects for both Mow and Herbicide, the interaction between them and interaction for the Farm and Paddock using poission distribution showed that the residual deviance was greater than the degrees of freedom (13124>784) Hence, the model is overdispersion and we need to fit the model by using quasipoisson. Note here, we have the better AIC is 17515.

As AIC could not be computed due to the GLM using quasipoisson, an estimate for R squared was calculated using 1 (Residual deviance/Null deviance). The was calculated as 0.8089526 (=1-(13124/68695)). This suggested that the model explains around 81% of the variability of the number of squares of bare ground. This estimate suggests that the model fit is relatively good.

The summary output of the GLM refitted with quasipoisson shows that Aminopyralid+triclopyr and Aminopyralid are significantly better at increasing number of 10cm x 10cm squares of bare ground in each plot. Because their p-value are very small(3.224015e-04 and 9.575650e-05 for HerbicideAminopyralid and HerbicideAminopyralid+triclopyr respectively) and their estimate values being positive values(0.3009473 and 0.3250091 for HerbicideAminopyralid and HerbicideAminopyralid+triclopyr respectively).

The red horizontal line on the Residuals vs Fitted plot showed that residuals were linear and did not show distinct patterns. The normal QQ plot showed that the residuals were fairly normally distributed and was not much deviation from normality. The scale-location plot illustrated a relatively horizontal red line slightly sloping up on the right and relatively equally spread points (apart from the cluster on the left which is the 0 values) hence showed homogeneity of variance of the residuals. The Residuals vs Leverage plot didnt show the red dashed lines, Cooks distance, so there were no values that were influential to the regression results. The only value of concern is 564 which has been highlighted in the plots. All assumptions for linear regression were met so this model was an appropriate model to use.

plot(glmm)

The summary output of the GLMM shows that no herbicide used, Aminopyralid, Aminopyralid+triclopyr, MCPA and MCPB were statistically significant as their p-values are very smaller(less than 0.05). So they are likely to have some association with the number of 10cm x 10cm squares of bare ground in each plot. However, Flumetsulam, MCPB+bentazone and Thifensulfuron-methyl have larger p-values (greater than 0.05), they are not statistically significant. So they probably do not have association with the numbear of 10cm x 10cmx squares of bare ground present in each plot.

All of the p-values of the interaction terms of herbicide and mow are very small (less than 0.05). Hence, all of the interaction effects of herbicide and mow are statistically significant. This means the relationship between herbicide and number of squares of bare ground depended on whether the plot has been mown or not. Also, we cannot interpret the main effects without considering the interaction effects.

The residual plot shows that the residuals are equally spread along the residual zero line. This suggests the assumption of the relationship is linear is reasonable. However, there are more data points are clustered on the left side of the plot and some data points are lying beyond the residual-zero line on the right side of the plot. This suggests the variance of the error terms are not equal.

4.

anova(glm1.1,glmm)
#AIC(glmm)

The AIC for these two models are similar. The disribution of deviance redisuals of these two models are about the same. The main difference between the two models is that the GLM model indicates that many of the herbicides are not associated with the number of 10cm x 10cm squares of bare grounds whereas, but more herbicides were associated with the number of 10cm x 10cm squares of bare ground in the GLMM fitted. So I think it is better to fit a GLMM and treat the farm_by_paddock as the random effect. The random intercept variance is 2.021, which gives the mean random effect variance of the model. Hence, GLMM is a better model for the data.

5.

The analysis suggests that the efficacy of different herbicides was high. Type of herbicide used is found to be associated with the number of 10cm x 10cm squares of bare ground. The efficacy of the management of pasture was also high as herbicides. The interaction term of these two was statistically insignificant which meant that herbicide efficacy and Mow efficacy could be interpreted independently. It would be advised for dairy farmers to focus both on use of certain herbicides and be concerned about the management of pasture when considering the number of bare ground in each plot.
